dex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExploring how technological apparatuses “capture” invisible worlds, this book looks at how spirits, UFOs, discarnate entities, spectral energies, atmospheric forces and particles are mattered into existence by human minds. Technological and scientific discourse has always been central to the nineteenth- and early twentieth-century spiritualist quest for legitimacy, but as this book shows, machines, people, and invisible beings are much more ontologically entangled in their definitions and constitution than we would expect. The book shows this entanglement through a series of contemporary case studies where the realm of the invisible arises through technological engagement, and where the paranormal intertwines with modern technology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aParapsychology and science. 0aTechnologyxMiscellanea. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aanimism.  aanthropology.  aatmospheric forces.  acultural.  adiscarnate entities.  aengaging.  aexperiments.  ahuman minds.  ainvisible beings.  ainvisible worlds.  alife and death.  amodern technology.  aotherworldly.  apage turner.  aparanormal.  aparticles.  areligion and spirituality.  ascience and math.  ascientific discourse.  ascientific exploration.  asocial science.  asocial.  aspectral energies.  aspiritual.  aspiritualism.  aspiritualists.  asupernatural.  atechnological apparatuses.  atechnological engagement.  atechnological.  atechnology studies.  aufos.1 aAlgranti, Miguel M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDippel, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEspírito Santo, Diana, eco